Everyone has heard the story of him gaining his mythic strength by carrying a young calf on his shoulder every day, while it slowly matured into a bull. Milo is known for being the "inventor" of progressive overload training.

Man of power: Milo of Croton. Ancient Greek, said to be one of the best wrestlers of all times.

Training routine, exercises and diet - a thread.

The initial part of the lift is basically a ZERCHER Deadlift - a very underrated form of the classic compound movement. The Zercherch DL will hit your traps and abdominals more and also help you with your balance. Even if you don't plan to do it regularly it is a good power test.

Of course, most modern gyms have various equipment but sadly a surprising lack of young bulls, so if we wish to follow his example we have to improvise: the motion of lifting a fully grown animal consists of a few steps, all of which we can imitate using a barbell.

The third (and most important) part would be the carrying of the bull through the village. Of course in a modern gym you would have trouble walking around with a heavy barbell upon your shoulders  so you're basically restricted to Farmer's walks - a monstrous exercise, which ...

In the push press you are able to use your legs to "assist" the movement, which allows you to lift bigger weights for more repetitions. Personally I enjoy the push press more than the OHP because it is a lot more "natural" motion, you already know the form by heart only!

The second part would be the bringing of the bull to the shoulders: which is similar to a push press (even though the barbell might actively try to fight you in the original version). The push press is very close to the classic overhead/military press (but with a few changes!)

Diet: it is said that Milo consumed 9 kilograms of meat. Recently many people have come to praise the nutritious value of meat and are starting to realize it is a needed part of a healthy diet. (shoutout to @0xa59a2d) Of course, if able always try to buy BIO/grass-fed or even...

... I guarantee will fug your forearms up! Carrying exercises work your muscles differently compared to lifting ones are an essential part of a routine if you strive to have a sculpture physique and simultaneously being tough, resistant and combat-ready.

Next: 9 kilograms of bread daily! So, Milo was not a big fan of keto it seems. Carb-loading was an essential part of his diet. Of course, the bread they had there was different from the one you buy in your supermarket. If possible, try to make bread yourself using yeast...

...better, buy from a farmer you know. It costs a bit more but believe me - by buying non-gmo non-antibiotics and hormones filled meat, you are also buying more time on this Earth and better health for yourself.

... (which is surprisingly easy to do!) or consider switching to another form of carbohydrates like potatoes or rice. The final part of his daily meals were a staggering 10 liters of wine! Obviously don't try that at home, but an occasional glass of wine never hurts!

If you go above three glasses you risk ruining the protein synthesis that happens in your body, thus nullifying your daily gains. Small doses of wine boost your immune system, help your heart and brain.

Modern science claims that wine is bad for you but I'm inclined not to agree. Wine is something essential: it is said that all human civilizations can be split into two groups - the savage ones who never invented wine, and the cultured ones that did! Don't drink too much though!

There is one final part... but I'll leave it secret for now and reveal it in the close future... For now, this was Milo of Croton, one of the mightiest men who ever graced this world with their existence, and here is his physique! Now go, lift, and become like Greeks yourselves!
